---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="About Soundings">
  <article>
    <h2>About Soundings</h2>
    <p>
      Soundings is an MCP server wrapping a curated set of UK open data
      sources behind a small surface of question-shaped tools. Ask about a
      place — postcode, council, region — and get coherent answers grounded
      in named sources.
    </p>

    <h3>How capture works</h3>
    <p>
      Every interaction with the server is logged as a structured record,
      with your consent. The published corpus becomes a public artefact in
      its own right under CC BY 4.0.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Full consent</strong> — your question text and self-declared
        sector are captured. The text is sanitised before publication
        (postcodes truncated to sector, personal names redacted via NER,
        small-charity names stripped).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Minimal consent (default)</strong> — only the structured
        fields are captured: which tool was called, the place, the indicators
        returned. Your question text is never stored.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No consent</strong> — nothing is captured. You can still use
        the server.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Change your choice any time using the banner at the top of every page.
      The chosen level applies to the rest of your session.
    </p>

    <h3>The corpus</h3>
    <p>
      Every month a sanitised snapshot of the question corpus is published
      as gzipped CSV and JSON Lines. The manifest records SHA-256 hashes,
      the catalogue version, the sanitisation rules version, and the git
      commit that produced it — so you can audit exactly what went in.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Phase 2 plan defers pushing the corpus to a hosted bucket; v1
      writes local artefacts only. See
      <a href="https://github.com/dataforaction-tom/soundings/blob/main/docs/adr/0004-corpus-publication.md">
        ADR-0004
      </a>.
    </p>

    <h3>The data behind every answer</h3>
    <p>
      Every page that shows indicator values also shows the SourceRef for
      each one: where it came from, when we retrieved it, and what cache
      status it has. A collapsed "data behind this" panel shows the raw
      tool call and response so you can see what the UI saw.
    </p>

    <h3>Links</h3>
    <ul>
